<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-712-657  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 712 657.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Dec 1 1990 v29 n23 p58(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Removing barriers to automation. (electronic design automationtools)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCann, Ray.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronic design automation (EDA) tools have not yet gainedacceptance in the computer-aided engineering (CAE) sector becauseof the lack of alternative forms of entry.andP;  Synthesis toolsemphasizing optimization and implementation efficiency requirethat designers conform to the vendor's design entry form.andP;  CAEtools must provide the entry form that is best for the design athand as well as for the designer to optimize productivity.andP;  Thefirst alternative entry forms were tools for handcrafted netlists,m digitized schematics and schematic capture, but very-high-speedintegrated circuit (VHSIC) hardware description languages (VHDL)soon followed.andP;  VHDL requires that designers learn a new entryform, however, which means another type of alternate form isnecessary that lets designers work in a familiar environment,gives them fast design entry and allows analysis tool access.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Design AutomationComputer-Aided DesignComputer-Aided EngineeringCircuit DesignSoftware PackagesNew TechniqueHardware Description Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>